Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, the most serious economic problem facing our nation today is the deadlock between labor and management in the steel industry.

14:41.920 --> 14:46.920
Negotiations, mediation and fact-finding swim around before the public's eye.

14:46.920 --> 14:52.920
In full-page advertisements placed by labor and management, each argues that the other is wrong.

14:52.920 --> 14:57.920
In the midst of this impasse, the public interests flounders and the consumer wonders.

14:57.920 --> 15:03.920
When the smoke is cleared away, well, John Cue public's pocketbook stagger under another blow.

15:03.920 --> 15:15.920
Where the price of paper clips and pots and pans and pumps and pyromores, and everything else, John Cue must buy, clam another rum on the ladder of inflation when the sound and fury have subsided.

15:16.920 --> 15:24.920
Well, why are big steel and the steel workers locked in this gigantic wrestling match, each with an identical hammer lock on the other?

15:24.920 --> 15:30.920
What are the conflicting positions of labor and management, which have produced this desperate draw?

15:30.920 --> 15:38.920
Management rests this case essentially on the assumption that the time has come to hold what it calls inflationary wage increases.

15:38.920 --> 15:44.920
Management also says that it must have higher profits in order to finance the future expansion of the industry.

15:45.920 --> 15:57.920
Labor bases its case largely upon the assumption that the steel companies can easily afford to grant a wage boost without incurring an increase in cost, because of the increase in labor productivity.

15:57.920 --> 16:03.920
Labor also believes profits of the steel companies are excessive and wants to share in these profits.

16:03.920 --> 16:08.920
Labor and management both insist that they have the consumers' interest at heart.

16:08.920 --> 16:16.920
Well, many facts have been produced from the series of administered price hearings before the antitrust and monopoly subcommittee of which I am chairman.

16:16.920 --> 16:26.920
This past week, one of the newest facts to reach the public came in the announcement by the steel companies themselves of their profits for the first half of this year.

16:26.920 --> 16:37.920
Profits after taxes for 14 companies accounting for three-fifths of the industry's capacity, jumped 145 percent over the first half of last year.

16:37.920 --> 16:46.920
The industry leader, United States Steel Corporation, was 28 percent of our steel making capacity, neted $255 million.

16:46.920 --> 16:51.920
This is 88 percent more than the US steel netted for the same period last year.

16:51.920 --> 16:56.920
Well, friends, we are face to face today with a fundamental problem in the steel industry.

16:56.920 --> 17:00.920
In the future, this problem is going to confront us in other industries.

17:00.920 --> 17:08.920
Our public policy always has been toward industry in the past, has been based on the theory of price competition.

17:08.920 --> 17:17.920
If any firm in a competitive industry makes an improvement which reduces its cost, it is assumed that it will reduce its prices accordingly.

17:17.920 --> 17:24.920
The other firms will have to make the improvement themselves or lose the business to the firm which made the improvement.

17:24.920 --> 17:35.920
The pioneering company gains increased business at least for a time, while the consumer receives the benefit of the innovation in the form of lower prices.

17:35.920 --> 17:41.920
But where there is no real price competition as in the steel industry, he just can't apply this theory.

17:41.920 --> 17:52.920
The problem we face today in non-competitive price industries is how to affect an equitable distribution of productivity gains made possible by scientific progress.

17:53.920 --> 17:59.920
Labor claims these gains, it argues that labor is being displaced by technological progress.

17:59.920 --> 18:09.920
Management bases its claims on the need for installation of new and better machinery and equipment, and it argues that greater profits are required for this.

18:09.920 --> 18:11.920
But the consumer has a claim too.

18:11.920 --> 18:20.920
John Cue Public argues that there is no purpose to scientific progress unless it results ultimately in lower prices or better products.

18:20.920 --> 18:31.920
While translating this into the context of the present steel controversy, I believe the consumer should continue to be the principal beneficiary of technological progress.

18:31.920 --> 18:49.920
I believe there is ample room without undue reduction in profits for price reduction and steel, together with a small increase in wages, preferably in the form of an increase in pensions, which would give greater time to enjoy life to the older workers and greater opportunity to the younger ones.

18:50.920 --> 19:04.920
Until this problem is faced with a nation and by all divisions of our government, I am afraid the wage-price spiral will keep spinning higher and higher, and the value of John Cue Public's dollar will plunge lower and lower, but I hope this is not going to be the case.

19:04.920 --> 19:07.920
Thank you until next week at this time.

