Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, without a doubt the most important development in Washington and in the world is the decision of President Eisenhower in Premier Nikita Kruciak to exchange visits in September and this fall.

19:33.920 --> 19:51.920
When this was announced that precipitated a flood of speculation all the way from full approval of the idea to outright opposition and indignation, some feel that this country is letting down the people of the free nations who have sided with us against the threat of communism.

19:51.920 --> 20:04.920
Some other people argue that people in the captive nations behind the Iron Curtain will feel that they have been abandoned and forgotten about with this new show of friendship.

20:04.920 --> 20:12.920
There is also concern that some incident might happen to Mr. Kruciak when he was here that would make tensions worse rather than easing them.

20:12.920 --> 20:20.920
We are all fully aware of these viewpoints, but I have faith in the sound, common sense, and judgment of our people.

20:20.920 --> 20:26.920
I do not think that Mr. Kruciak's visit to this country will pull the eyes over any of our people.

20:26.920 --> 20:43.920
I do think that this is a chance to show Mr. Kruciak the prosperity and the strength of America and that it might give him a second to so bring thought that he is laboring under any idea about our material strength or our spiritual stamina.

20:44.920 --> 20:51.920
I think that people of all nations of the world are acutely concerned with a nuclear threat that hangs over our heads.

20:51.920 --> 20:58.920
Our nation will spend more than $40 billion this year for missiles, for defense, for powder and for guns.

20:58.920 --> 21:03.920
We simply cannot go on with this kind of military expenditure.

21:03.920 --> 21:12.920
We would like to use some of this money for other and good social things, hospitals, schools, and things that our people need.

21:12.920 --> 21:22.920
The Cold War requires Russia to divert tremendous outlays from its economic development into support of its large military commitments.

21:22.920 --> 21:32.920
The vision of destruction and death that a nuclear attack and counterattack would mean is a sober and terrifying one.

21:32.920 --> 21:41.920
The cold hard fact is that there is no alternative to peace, and this becomes more an indescapable conclusion every day.

21:42.920 --> 21:52.920
Any avenue that can turn Premier Kruciak and the world away from a deadly march toward war is an avenue that we must and that we ought to explore.

21:52.920 --> 22:09.920
His visit to the United States and President Eisenhower's visit to the Soviet Union is maybe one of these ways to turn the thoughts of the people of the world to other avenues and is one that ought to be explored.

22:09.920 --> 22:16.920
You will note that the President intends to visit with the leaders of Western Europe before he goes to Moscow.

22:16.920 --> 22:26.920
And I think this is good. They naturally have a great many anxieties that some agreement might be made that would bind them, if they were not advised of.

22:26.920 --> 22:35.920
And of course any major policy decision must be made in conjunction with our loyal allies of the West.

22:36.920 --> 22:48.920
After all this is a new course for the United States and for the world, and it should be explained to our allies and to the friends that we have in the non-committed nations of the world before in this step is taken.

22:48.920 --> 22:55.920
And no great settlement I don't think is going to come from the exchange of visits of President Eisenhower and Mr. Kruciak.

22:55.920 --> 23:01.920
Such cannot result in independent action without the participation of our allies.

23:01.920 --> 23:13.920
But if nothing more results than the easing of tension and the relaxation of difficulties generated over the Berlin crisis, certainly we can say that some progress has been made.

23:13.920 --> 23:18.920
As long as we are talking, we are not fighting and we are not dying.

23:18.920 --> 23:28.920
And so I welcome the opportunity our people now have of showing Mr. Kruciak our wonderful country and what we have here in the United States.

23:29.920 --> 23:44.920
And I have suggested to the President that Mr. Kruciak's list of American visits include the Tennessee Valley Authority region, where he will see a fine example of democracy and action and I know personally that he is interested.

23:44.920 --> 23:53.920
Also that he goes to Nashville and see the state capital and here the Grand Ole Opry and visit the Permitage. That's all for now. Thank you very much.

23:59.920 --> 24:00.920
Thank you.

